{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477376","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477376"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:00:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14338"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14338","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14338"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.1,0.08,0.09,0.67]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7033"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55759"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7033","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7033"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14338"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41303"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1466"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16737"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17213"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44208"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55759"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-week-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with his parents due to frequent vomiting over the past week. The vomiting is described as forceful and projectile, occurring after most feeds. The vomitus is non-bilious. He was born at term with no complications and has been growing well until this week. He has no significant medical history and takes no medications. On examination, he appears slightly dehydrated but alert. His pulse rate is 150/min, blood pressure 80/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 40/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft and non-tender. No masses are palpable. Visible peristaltic waves are noted in the epigastrium just before episodes of vomiting.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Upper gastrointestinal endoscopy","Abdominal X-ray","Serum electrolytes","Barium swallow","Abdominal ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a classic picture of pyloric stenosis, which typically affects male infants around 3-6 weeks of age. The hallmark symptom is projectile, non-bilious vomiting, which this patient demonstrates. The visible peristaltic waves in the epigastrium are also characteristic of this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is the diagnostic test of choice for pyloric stenosis. It can directly visualize the hypertrophied pyloric muscle and measure its thickness and length. Diagnostic criteria typically include a pyloric muscle thickness greater than 3-4 mm and a pyloric channel length greater than 14-18 mm. Ultrasound is non-invasive, does not involve radiation, and has high sensitivity and specificity for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBarium swallow\u003C/strong\u003E was historically used to diagnose pyloric stenosis, showing the classic \u0027string sign\u0027 or \u0027shoulder sign\u0027. However, it has largely been replaced by ultrasound due to the latter\u0027s superior accuracy and lack of radiation exposure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbdominal X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically useful in diagnosing pyloric stenosis. It may show a distended stomach but cannot directly visualize the pyloric muscle hypertrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUpper gastrointestinal endoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E is unnecessarily invasive for the initial diagnosis of pyloric stenosis. While it could potentially visualize the narrowed pyloric channel, it is not the first-line diagnostic test for this condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum electrolytes\u003C/strong\u003E, while often deranged in pyloric stenosis due to loss of stomach acid (typically showing hypochloremic, hypokalemic metabolic alkalosis), are not diagnostic. They may be checked as part of the initial workup, but would not be considered the next step in diagnosis. However, they are important to guide fluid and electrolyte replacement before surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s worth noting that in some cases, an olive-shaped mass (the hypertrophied pylorus) may be palpable in the right upper quadrant. This finding is pathognomonic for pyloric stenosis but was not detected in this patient. The absence of a palpable mass does not rule out the diagnosis, and ultrasound remains the most appropriate next step.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESeveral risk factors are associated with pyloric stenosis. These include male sex (as in this case), with males being four times more likely to be affected than females. Other risk factors include being first-born, Caucasian ethnicity, family history (30-fold increased risk), preterm birth, and bottle feeding. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce diagnosed, treatment for pyloric stenosis involves two main steps. First, fluid resuscitation is crucial to correct dehydration and electrolyte imbalances caused by persistent vomiting. This typically involves intravenous fluid administration and correction of any metabolic alkalosis. Once the patient is stabilized, the definitive treatment is surgical. A pyloromyotomy, usually performed laparoscopically, involves cutting the hypertrophied pyloric muscle to relieve the obstruction. This procedure has excellent outcomes, with most infants able to resume feeding within hours of surgery and achieve full recovery.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Pyloric stenosis typically presents in male infants around 3-6 weeks of age with projectile, non-bilious vomiting.","Palpation of an olive-shaped mass in the right upper quadrant is pathognomonic for pyloric stenosis.","Ultrasound is the diagnostic test of choice for pyloric stenosis, measuring pyloric muscle thickness and length."],"references":["Garfield K, Sergent SR. Pyloric Stenosis. 2023 Jan 30. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32310391.","Fujimoto, T. (2020). Infantile Hypertrophic Pyloric Stenosis. In: Puri, P. (eds) Pediatric Surgery. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg. https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-662-43588-5_60"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41303"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14338"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41303","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41303"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-17T20:28:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-17T20:28:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7033"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55759"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"em